3. Data Visualisation

3.2 First Steps

3.2.1

Run ggplot(data = mpg). What do you see?

ggplot(data = mpg)

How many rows are in mpg? How many columns?

3.2.3

What does the drv variable describe? Read the help for ?mpg to find out.

?mpg

drv = the type of drive train, where f = front-wheel drive, r = rear wheel drive, 4 = 4wd.

3.2.4

Make a scatterplot of hwy vs cyl.

mpg %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = hwy, y = cyl)) + 
  geom_point()

3.2.5

What happens if you make a scatterplot of class vs drv? Why is the plot not useful?

mpg %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = class, y = drv)) + 
  geom_point()

3.3 Mapping Aesthetics

3.3.1

What’s gone wrong with this code? Why are the points not blue?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = "blue"))

Colour is within the aesthetic mapping of the data. It should be this:

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy), colour = "blue")

3.3.2

Which variables in mpg are categorical? Which variables are continuous? (Hint: type ?mpg to read the documentation for the dataset). How can you see this information when you run mpg?

mpg
## # A tibble: 234 x 11
##    manufacturer model      displ  year   cyl trans drv     cty   hwy fl    class
##    <chr>        <chr>      <dbl> <int> <int> <chr> <chr> <int> <int> <chr> <chr>
##  1 audi         a4           1.8  1999     4 auto~ f        18    29 p     comp~
##  2 audi         a4           1.8  1999     4 manu~ f        21    29 p     comp~
##  3 audi         a4           2    2008     4 manu~ f        20    31 p     comp~
##  4 audi         a4           2    2008     4 auto~ f        21    30 p     comp~
##  5 audi         a4           2.8  1999     6 auto~ f        16    26 p     comp~
##  6 audi         a4           2.8  1999     6 manu~ f        18    26 p     comp~
##  7 audi         a4           3.1  2008     6 auto~ f        18    27 p     comp~
##  8 audi         a4 quattro   1.8  1999     4 manu~ 4        18    26 p     comp~

## 10 audi         a4 quattro   2    2008     4 manu~ 4        20    28 p     comp~
## # ... with 224 more rows

displ (engine displacement), cty (city miles per gallon), and hwy (highway miles per gallon) are all continuous variables. The rest are categorical.

3.3.3

Map a continuous variable to color, size, and shape. How do these aesthetics behave differently for categorical vs. continuous variables?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, colour = cty))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = cty))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = cty))

3.3.4

What happens if you map the same variable to multiple aesthetics?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = hwy, colour = displ))

This mapping is redundant. One variable should be assigned to one mapping.

3.3.5

What does the stroke aesthetic do? What shapes does it work with? (Hint: use ?geom_point)

ggplot(mtcars, aes(wt, mpg)) +
  geom_point(shape = 21, colour = "purple", fill = "green", size = 5, stroke = 5)

Changes border of points. geom_point also has other aesthetics such as colour, shape, fill, etc.

3.3.6

What happens if you map an aesthetic to something other than a variable name, like aes(colour = displ \< 5)? Note, you’ll also need to specify x and y.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, colour = displ > 5))

Colours observations according to boolean values (TRUE vs FALSE)

3.5 Facets

3.5.1

What happens if you facet on a continuous variable?

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(. ~ cty)

The contiuous variable is converted into a categorical variable and a facet is plotted for each distinct value.

3.5.2

What do the empty cells in plot with facet_grid(drv \~ cyl) mean? How do they relate to this plot?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = drv, y = cyl))

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

The empty facets correlate to missing points in the first plot.

3.3.3

What plots does the following code make? What does . do?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

. ignores that dimension when facetting. The first facet_grid(hwy \~ .) creates facets along the y-axis, the second facet_grid(. \~ cyl) creates facets along the x-axis.

3.3.4

Take the first faceted plot in this section:

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

What are the advantages to using faceting instead of the colour aesthetic? What are the disadvantages? How might the balance change if you had a larger dataset?

Colour aesthetics make it easier to view differences across x and y axis. Whereas faceting makes it easier to look at a higher number of categories since each one is mapped on a different plot.

3.5.5

Read ?facet_wrap. What does nrow do? What does ncol do? What other options control the layout of the individual panels? Why doesn’t facet_grid() have nrow and ncol arguments?

nrow and ncol respectively sets number of rows and columns to facet wrap. facet_grid doesn’t have this as these are taken from the arguments for x and y axis.

3.5.6

When using facet_grid() you should usually put the variable with more unique levels in the columns. Why?

More space for columns in landscape images.

3.6 Geometric Objects

3.6.1

What geom would you use to draw a line chart? A boxplot? A histogram? An area chart?

  • line chart: geom_line()
  • boxplot: geom_boxplot()
  • histogram: geom_histogram()
  • area chart: geom_area()

3.6.2

Run this code in your head and predict what the output will look like. Then, run the code in R and check your predictions.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

3.6.3

What does show.legend = FALSE do? What happens if you remove it? Why do you think I used it earlier in the chapter?

Removes the legend box.

3.6.4

What does the se argument to geom_smooth() do?

Shows the standard error bands.

3.6.5

Will these two graphs look different? Why/why not?

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

geom_point and geom_smooth inherits the same mappings from ggplot(mapping = aes())

3.6.6

Recreate the R code necessary to generate the following graphs.

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, line = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, colour = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, colour = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, colour = drv, colour = drv, linetype = drv)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, colour = drv)) + 
  geom_point(size = 4, colour = "white") +
  geom_point(aes(colour = drv))

3.7 Statistical Transformations

3.7.1

What is the default geom associated with stat_summary()? How could you rewrite the following plot to use that geom function instead of the stat function?

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  stat_summary(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth),
    fun.min = min,
    fun.max = max,
    fun = median
  )

Default geom for stat_summary() is geom_pointrange, but the default stat for geom_pointrange is ‘identity’.

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_pointrange(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth),
    stat = 'summary',
    fun.max = max,
    fun.min = min,
    fun = median
  )

3.7.2

What does geom_col() do? How is it different to geom_bar()? geom_col() by default uses stat_identity(), leaves the data as is and expects both x and y mappings. geom_bar by default uses stat_count, only expects an x mapping and calculates the number of observations for each value of x.

3.7.4

What variables does stat_smooth() compute? What parameters control its behaviour?

?stat_smooth

geom_smooth and stat_smooth are aliases and use the same arguments. These methods/arguments are: - method: smoothing method. e.g. NULL, lm, glm, loess. - formula: customiing smoothing method - se: If TRUE, displays standard error bands. - na.rm: missing values are removed with FALSE or without TRUE error messages.

Computed variables of stat_smooth include: - y: predicted values - ymin: lower value of the confidence interval - ymax: upper value of confidence interval - se: standard error

3.7.5

In our proportion bar chart, we need to set group = 1. Why? In other words what is the problem with these two graphs?

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = after_stat(prop)))

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = after_stat(prop)))

From ?geom_bar: geom_bar() makes the height of the bar proportional to the number of cases in each group. Proportions are calculated within each group so they all have the same height. The correct plot is:

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = stat(prop), group = 1))

3.8 Position adjustments

3.8.1

What is the problem with this plot? How could you improve it?

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point()

There are missing observations in this plot because they are stacked. We can apply a jitter (random noise displacement) to each observation so they are less likely to stack. This reduces accuracy.
Use geom_jitter or add a position = "jitter" argument to geom_point.

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(position = "jitter" )

### 3.8.2 > What parameters to geom_jitter() control the amount of jittering?

  • width: controls horizontal jitter
  • height: controls vertical jitter

3.8.3

Compare and contrast geom_jitter() with geom_count.

  • geom_jitter adds random noise to displace observations on the graph, thereby reducing overplotting but also accuracy.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_jitter()

  • geom_count sizes points according to relative number of observations. eg.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = cty, y = hwy)) +
  geom_count()
